<P>Emily enquired if &s;he had ever heard
the &s;ervants talk of pri&s;oners.</P>
<P>&startq;Ah ma'am&s;elle!&endq; &s;aid Annette archly,
&startq;now I dare &s;ay you are thinking of
Mon&s;ieur Valancourt, and that he may
have come among the armies, which, they
&s;ay, are come from our country, to fight
again&s;t this &s;tate, and that he has met with
&s;ome of <HI>cur</HI> people, and is taken captive.
O Lord! how glad I &s;hould be, if it was &s;o!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Woul'd you, indeed, be glad?&endq; &s;aid
Emily, in a tone of mournful reproach.</P>
<P>&startq;To be &s;ure I &s;hould, ma'am,&endq; replied
<PB N="139" REF="141">
Annette,&endq; and would not you be glad too,
to &s;ee Signor Valancourt? I don't know
any chevalier I like better, I have a very
great regard for the Signor, truly.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Your regard for him cannot be doubt|ed&endq;
&s;aid Emily, &startq;&s;ince you wi&s;h to &s;ee
him a pri&s;oner.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Why no, ma'am&s;elle, not a pri&s;oner
either; but one mu&s;t be glad to &s;ee him,
you know. And it was only the other
night I dreamt&mdash;I dreamt I &s;aw him drive
into the ca&s;tle-yard all in a coach and &s;ix,
and dre&s;&s;ed out, with a laced coat and a
&s;word, like a lord as he is.&endq;</P>
<P>Emily could not forbear &s;miling at An|nette's
ideas of &startq;Valancourt, and repeated
her enquiry, whether &s;he had heard the
&s;ervants talk of pri&s;oners.</P>
<P>&startq;No, ma'am&s;elle,&endq; replied &s;he,&startq;never;
and lately they have done nothing but
talk of the apparition, that has been walk|ing
about of a night on the ramparts, and
that frightened the&punc;&s;entinels into fits. It
came among them like a fla&s;h of fire, they
<PB N="140" REF="142">
&s;ay, and they all fell down in a row, till
they came to them&s;elves again; and then
it was gone, and nothing to be &s;een but
the old ca&s;tle walls; &s;o they helped one
another up again as fa&s;t as they could.
You would not believe, ma'am&s;elle, though
I &s;hewed you the very cannon, where it
u&s;ed to appear.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And are you, indeed, &s;o &s;imple, An|nette,&endq;
&s;aid Emily, &s;miling-at this curious
exaggeration of the circum&s;tance &s;he had
witne&s;&s;ed, &startq;as to credit the&s;e &s;tories?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Credit them, ma'am&s;elle! why all the
world could not per&s;uade me out of them.
Roberto and Seba&s;tian and half a dozen
more of them went into fits! To be &s;ure,
there was no occa&s;ion for that; I &s;aid, my|&s;elf,
there was no need of that, for, &s;ays
I, when the enemy comes, what a pretty
figure they will cut, if they are to fall
down in fits, all of a row! The enemy won't
be &s;o civil, perhaps, as to walk off, like
the gho&s;t, and leave them to help one
another up, but will fall to, cutting and
<PB N="141" REF="143">
&s;la&s;hing, till he makes them all ri&s;e up
dead men. No, no, &s;ays I, there is rea&s;on
in all things: though I might have fallen
down in a fit, that was no rule for them,
being, becau&s;e it is no bu&s;ine&s;s of mine
to look gruff and fight battles.&endq;</P>
<P>Emily endeavoured to correct the &s;u|per&s;titious
weakne&s;s of Annette, though
&s;he could not entirely &s;ubdue her own;
to which the latter only replied, &startq;Nay,
ma'am&s;elle, you will believe nothing; you
are almo&s;t as bad as the Signor him&s;elf,
who was in a great pa&s;&s;ion when they told
him of what had happened, and &s;wore
that the fir&s;t man, who repeated &s;uch non|&s;en&s;e,
&s;ould be thrown into the dungeon
under the ea&s;t turret. This was a hard
puni&s;hment too, for only talking non|&s;en&s;e,
as he called it, but I dare &s;ay he
had other rea&s;ons for calling it &s;o, than
you have, ma'am&endq;</P>
<P>Emily looked di&s;plea&s;ed, and made no
reply. As &s;he mu&s;ed upon the recollected
appearance, which had lately &s;o much
<PB N="142" REF="144">
alarmed her, and con&s;idered the circum|&s;tances
of the figure having &s;tationed it&s;elf
oppo&s;ite to her ca&s;ement, &s;he was for a
moment inclined to believe it was Valan|court,
whom &s;he had &s;een. Yet, if it was
he, why did&punc; he not &s;peak to her, when he
had. the, opportunity of doing &s;o&mdash;and, if
he was a pri&s;oner in the ca&s;tle, and he
could be here in no other character, how
could he obtain the means of walking
abroad on the rampart? Thus &s;he was
utterly unabtle to decide&punc; whether the
mu&s;ician and the form &s;he had ob&s;erved,
were the &s;ame, or, if they were whether
this was Valancourt. She, however, de|&s;ired,
that Annette would endeavour to
learn whether any pri&s;oners were in the
ca&s;tle, and al&s;o, their names.</P>
<P>&startq;O dear, ma'am&s;elle!&endq; &s;aid Annette,
&startq;I forget to tell you what you bade mea&s;k
about, the ladies, as they call them&s;elves,
who are lately come to Udolpho. Why
that Signora Livona, that the Signor
brought to &s;ee my late lady at Venice, is
<PB N="143" REF="145">
his mi&s;tre&s;s now, and was little better
then, I dare &s;ay. And Ludovico &s;ays
(but pray be &s;ecret, ma'am) that his <HI>Ex|cellenza</HI>
introduced her only to impo&s;e
upon the world, that had begun to make
free with her character. So when people
&s;aw my! lady notice her, they thought what
they had heard mu&s;t be &s;candal. The
other two are the mi&s;tre&s;&s;es of Signor Ve|rezzi
and Signor Bertolini; and Signor
Montoni invited them all to the ca&s;tle;
and &s;o, ye&s;terday, he gave a great enter|tainment;
and there they were, all drinking
Tu&s;cany wine and all &s;orts, and laughing
and &s;inging, till they made the ca&s;tle ring
again. But I thought they were di&s;mal
&s;ounds, &s;o &s;oon after my poor lady's death
too; and they, brought to my mind what
&s;he would have thought, if &s;he had heard
them&mdash;but &s;he cannot hear them now,
poor &s;oul! &s;aid I.&endq;</P>
<P>Emily turned away to conceal her emo|tion,
and then de&s;ired Annette to&punc; go, and
make enquiry, concerning the pri&s;oners,
<PB N="144" REF="146">
that might be in the ca&s;tle, but conjured
her to do it with caution, and on no ac|count
to mention her name, or that of
Mon&s;ieur Valancourt.</P>
<P>&startq;Now I think of it, ma'am&s;elle,&endq; &s;aid
Annette, &startq;I do believe there are pri&s;on|ers,
for I overheard one of the Signor's
men, ye&s;terday, in the &s;ervants hall, talk|ing
&s;omething about ran&s;oms,&punc; and &s;aying
what a fine thing it was for his <HI>sExcellenza</HI>
to catch up men, and they were as good
booty as any other, becau&s;e of the ran&s;oms.
And the other man was grumbling, and
&s;aying it was fine enough for the Signor,
but none &s;o fine for his &s;oldiers, becau&s;e,
&s;aid he, we don't go &s;hares there.&endq;</P>
<P>This information heightened&punc; Emily's
impatience to know more, and Annette
immediately departed on her enquiry.</P>
<P>The late re&s;olution of Emily to re&s;ign
her e&s;tates to Montoni, now gave way to
new con&s;iderations; the po&s;&s;ibility, that
Valancourt was near her, revived her for|titude
and &s;he determined to brave the
<PB N="145" REF="147">
threatened vengeance, at lea&s;t, till &s;he
could be a&s;&s;ured whether he was really in
the ca&s;tle. She was in this temper of
mind, when t&s;e received a me&s;&s;age from
Montoni, requiring her attendance in the
cedar parlour, which &s;he obeyed with
trembling, and, on 'her way thi$her, en|deavoured
to animate her fortitude with
the idea of Valancourt.</P>
<P>Montoni was alone. &startq;I &s;ent for you,&endq;
&s;aid he, &startq;to give you another opportunity
of retracting your late mi&s;taken-a&s;&s;ertions
concerning the Languedoc e&s;tates. I will
conde&s;cend to advi&s;e, where I may com|mand.
&mdash;If you are really deluded by an
opinion, that you have any $ight to the&s;e
e&s;tates, at lea&s;t, do not per&s;i&s;t in the error
&mdash;an error, which you may perceive, too
late, has been fatal to you. Dare my re|&s;entment
$o further, but &s;ign the papers.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;If I have no right in the&s;e e&s;tates, &s;ir,&endq;
&s;aid Emily, &startq;of what &s;ervice can it be to
you, that I &s;hould &s;ign any papers, con|cerning
them? If the lands are yours by
<PB N="146" REF="148">
law, you certainly may po&s;&s;e&s;s them, with|out
my interference, or my con&s;ent.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;I will have no more argument,&endq; &s;aid
Montoni, with a look that made her trem|ble.
&startq;What had I but trouble to expect,
when I conde&s;cended to rea&s;on with a baby!
But I will be trifled with no longer: let
the&punc; recollection of your aunt's &s;ufferings,
in con&s;equence of her folly and ob&s;tinacy,
teach you a le&s;&s;on.&mdash;Sign the papers.&endq;</P>
<P>Emily's re&s;olution was for a moment
awed:&mdash;&s;he &s;hrunk at the recollections he
revived, and from the vengeance he threat|ened;
but then, the image of Valancourt,
who &s;o long had loved her, and who was
now,&punc; perhaps, &s;o near her, came to her
heart, and, together with the &s;trong feelings
of indignation, with which &s;he had always,
from her infancy, regarded an act of in|ju&s;tice,
in&s;pired her with a noble, though
imprudent, courage.</P>
<P>&startq;Sign the papers,&endq; &s;aid Montoni,
more impatiently than before.</P>
<P>&startq;Never, &s;ir,&endq; replied Emily; &startq;that re|que&s;t
<PB N="147" REF="149">
would have proved to me the in|ju&s;tice of your claim,
had I even been ig|norant
of my right.&endq;</P>
<P>Montoni turned pale with anger,
while his quivering lip and lurking eye
made her almo&s;t repent the boldne&s;s of her
&s;peech.</P>
<P>&startq;Then all my vengeance falls upon you,&endq;
he exclaimed, with an horrible oath. &startq;And
think not it &s;hall be delayed. Neither the
e&s;tates in Languedoc, or Ga&s;cony, &s;hall be
yours; you have dared to que&s;tion my
right,&mdash;now dare to que&s;tion my power.
I have a puni&s;hment which you think not
of; it is terrible! This night&mdash;this very
night&endq;&mdash;</P>
<P>&startq;This night!&endq; repeated another voice.</P>
<P>Montoni pau&s;ed, and turned half round,
but, &s;eeming to recollect him&s;elf, he pro|ceeded
in a lower tone.</P>
<P>&startq;You have lately &s;een one terrible ex|ample
of ob&s;tinacy and folly; yet this, it appears,
has not been &s;ufficient to deter
<PB N="148" REF="150">
you.&mdash;I could tell you of others&mdash;I could
make you tremble at the bare recital.&endq;</P>
<P>He was interrupted by a groan, which
&s;eemed to ri&s;e from underneath the cham|ber
they were in; and, as he threw a glance
round it, impatience and rage &s;la&s;hed from
his eyes, yet &s;omething like a &s;hade of fear
pa&s;&s;ed over his countenance. Emily &s;at
down in a chair, near the door, for the va|rious
emotions &s;he had &s;uffered, now almo&s;t
overcame her; but Montoni pau&s;ed
&s;carcely an in&s;tant, and, commanding his
features, re&s;umed his di&s;cour&s;e in a lower,
yet &s;terner voice.</P>
<P>&startq;I &s;ay, I could give you other in&s;tances
of my power and of my character, which
it &s;eems you do not under&s;tand, or you
would not defy me.&mdash;I could tell you,
that, when once my re&s;olution is taken&mdash;
but I am talking to a baby. Let me, how|ever,
repeat, that terrible as are the exam|ples
I could recite, the recital could not now
benefit you; for, though, your re|pentance
<PB N="149" REF="151">
pentance would put an immediate end to
oppo&s;ition, it would not now appea&s;e my
indignation.&mdash;I will have vengeance as well
as ju&s;tice.&endq;</P>
<P>Another groan filled the pau&s;e which
Montoni made.</P>
<P>&startq;Leave the room in&s;tantly!&endq; &s;aid he,
&s;eeming not to notice this &s;trange occur|rence.
Without power to implore his
pity, &s;he ro&s;e to go, but found that &s;he
could not &s;upport her&s;elf; awe and terror
overcame her, and &s;he &s;unk again into
the chair.</P>
<P>&startq;Quit my pre&s;ence!&endq; cried Montoni,
&startq;This affectation of fear ill becomes the
heroine who has ju&s;t dared to brave my in|dignation.</P>
<P>&startq;Did you hear nothing, Signor?&endq; &s;aid
Emily, trembling, and &s;till unable to leave
the room.</P>
<P>&startq;I heard my own voice,&endq; rejoined
Montoni, &s;ternly.</P>
<P>&startq;And nothing el&s;e?&endq; &s;aid Emily,
<PB N="150" REF="152">
&s;peaking with difficulty.&mdash;&startq;There again!
Do you hear nothing now?&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Obey my order,&endq; repeated Montoni.
&startq;And for the&s;e fool's tricks&mdash;I will &s;oon
di&s;cover by whom they are practi&s;ed.&endq;</P>
<P>Emily again ro&s;e, and exerted her&s;elf to
the utmo&s;t to leave the room, while Mon|toni
followed her; but, in&s;tead of calling
aloud to his &s;ervants to &s;earch the chamber,
as he had formerly done on a &s;imilar oc|currence,
pa&s;ted to the ramparts.</P>
<P>As, in her way to the corridor, &s;he re&s;ted
for a moment at an open ca&s;ement,
Emily &s;aw a party of Montoni's troops
winding down a di&s;tant mountain, whom
&s;he noticed no further, than as they brought
to her mind the wretched pri&s;oners they
were, perhaps, bringing to the ca&s;tle. At
length, having reached her apartment, &s;he
threw her&s;elf upon the couch, overcome
with rhe new horrors of her &s;ituation. Her
thoughts lo&s;t in tumult and perplexity,
&s;he could neither repent of, or approve, her
<PB N="151" REF="153">
late conduct; &s;he could only remember,
that &s;he was in the power of a man, who
had no principle of action&mdash;but his will;
and the a&s;toni&s;hment and terrors of &s;uper|&s;tition,
which had, for a moment, &s;o &s;trongly
af&s;ailed her, now yielded to tho&s;e of
rea&s;on.</P>
<P>She was, at length, rou&s;ed from the re|verie,
which engaged her, by a confu&s;ion of
di&s;tant voices, and a clattering of hoofs,
that &s;eemed to come, on the wind, from the
courts. A &s;udden hope, that &s;ome good,
was approaching, &s;eized her mind, till &s;he
remembered the troops &s;he had ob&s;erved
from, the ca&s;ement, and concluded this to
be the party, which Annette had &s;aid were
expected at Udolpho.</P>
<P>Soon after, &s;he heard voices faintly from
the halls, and the noife of hor&s;es' feet &s;unk
away in the wind; &s;ilence en&s;ued. Emily
li&s;tened anxiou&s;ly for Annette's &s;tep in the
corridor, but a pau&s;e of total &s;tillne&s;s conti|nued,
till again the ca&s;tle &s;eemed to be all
tumult and confu&s;ion. She heard the echoes
<PB N="152" REF="154">
of many foot&s;teps, pa&s;&s;ing to and fro in the
halls and avenues below, and then bu&s;y
tongues were loud on the rampart. Hav|ing
hurried to her ca&s;ement, &s;he perceived
Montoni, with &s;ome of his officers, leaning
on the walls, and pointing from them;
while &s;everal &s;oldiers were employed at
the further end of the rampart about &s;ome
cannon; and &s;he continued to ob&s;erve
them, carele&s;s of the pa&s;&s;ing time.</P>
<P>Annette at length appeared, but brought
no intelligence of Valancourt, &startq;For, ma'am|&s;elle,&endq;
&s;aid &s;he,&startq;all the people pretend to
know nothing about any pri&s;oners. But
here is a fine piece of bu&s;ine&s;s! The re&s;t
of the party are ju&s;t arrived, ma'am; they
came &s;campering in as if they would have
broken their necks; one &s;carcely knew
whether the man, or his hor&s;e would get
within the gates fir&s;t. And they have
brought word&mdash;and &s;uch news! they have
brought word, that a party of the enemy,
as they call them, are coming towards the
ca&s;tle; &s;o we &s;hall have all the officers of,
<PB N="153" REF="155">
ju&s;tice, I &s;uppo&s;e, be&s;ieging it! all tho&s;e
terrible-looking fellows one u&s;ed to &s;ee at
Venice.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Thank God! exclaimed Emily, fer|vently,
&startq;there is yet a hope left for me,
then!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;What mean you ma'am&s;elle? Do
you wi&s;h to fall into the hands of tho&s;e
&s;ad-looking men! Why I u&s;ed to &s;hudder
as I pa&s;&s;ed them, and &s;hould have gue&s;&s;ed
what they were, if Ludovico had not told
me.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;We cannot be in wor&s;e hands than at
pre&s;ent,&endq; replied Emily, unguardedly;
&startq;but what rea&s;on have you to &s;uppo&s;e the&s;e
are officers of ju&s;tice?&endq;</P>
<P>Why <HI>our</HI> people, ma'am, are all in
&s;uch a fright, and a fu&s;s; and I don't know
any thing but the fear of ju&s;tice, that could
make them &s;o. I u&s;ed to think nothing on
earth could flu&s;ter them, unle&s;s, indeed, it
was a gho&s;t, or &s;o; but now, &s;ome of them
are for hiding down in the vaults under the
ca&s;tle; but you mu&s;t not tell the Signor
<PB N="154" REF="156">
this, ma'am&s;elle, and I overheard two of
them talking&mdash;Holy Mother! what
makes you look &s;o &s;ad, ma'am&s;elle? You
don't hear what I &s;ay!&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Yes, I do, Annette; pray proceed.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Well, ma'am&s;elle, all the ca&s;tle is in
&s;uch hurly-burly. Some of the men are
loading the cannon, and &s;ome are examin|ing
the great gates, and the walls all round,
and are hammering and patching up, ju&s;t
as if all tho&s;e repairs had never been made,
that were &s;o long about. But what is to
become of me and you, ma'am&s;elle, and
Ludovico? O! when I hear the &s;ound of
the cannon, I &s;hall die with fright. If I
could but catch the great. gate open for one
minute, I would be even with it for &s;hut|ting
me within the&s;e walls &s;o long!&mdash;it
&s;hould never &s;ee me again.&endq;</P>
<P>Emily caught the latter words of An|nette.
&endq;O! if you could find it open,
but for one moment!&endq; &s;he exclaimed&endq; my
peace might yet. be &s;aved!&endq; The heavy
groan &s;he uttered, and the wildne&s;s of her
<PB N="155" REF="157">
look, terrified Annette, &s;till more than her
words; who entreated Emily to explain
the meaning of them, to whom it &s;uddenly
occurred, that Ludovico might be of &s;ome
&s;ervice, if there &s;hould be a po&s;&s;ibility of
e&s;cape, and who repeated the &s;ub&s;tance of
what had pa&s;&s;ed between Montoni and
her&s;elf, but conjured her to mention this
to no per&s;on. except to Ludovico.&endq; It
may, perhaps, be in his power,&endq; &s;he added,
&endq;to effect our e&s;cape. Go to him, An|nette,
tell him what I have to apprehend,
and what I have already &s;uffered; but en|treat
him to be &s;ecret, and to lo&s;e no time
in attempting to relea&s;e us. If he is wil|ling
to undertake this he &s;hall be amply
rewarded. I cannot &s;peak with him my|&s;elf,
for we might be ob&s;erved and then
effectual care would be taken to prevent
our flight. But be quick, Annette, and,
above all, be di&s;creet&mdash;I will await your
return in this apartment.&endq;</P>
<P>The girl, who&s;e hone&s;t heart had been
much aflfected by the recital, was now as
<PB N="156" REF="158">
eager to obey, as Emily was to employ
her, and &s;he immediately quitted the
room.</P>
<P>Emily's &s;urpri&s;e increa&s;ed, as &s;he reflected
upon Annette's intelligence.&endq;Alas!&endq;
&s;aid &s;he,&endq; what can the officers of ju&s;tice
do again&s;t an armed ca&s;tle? the&s;e cannot
be &s;uch&endq; Upon further con&s;ideration,
however, &s;he concluded, that, Montoni's
bands having plundered the country round,
the inhabitants had taken arms, and were
coming with the officers of police and a
party of &s;oldiers, to force their way into
the ca&s;tle.&endq; But they know not,&endq; thought
&s;he,&endq; its &s;trength, or the armed numbers
within it. Alas! except from flight, I
have nothing to hope!&endq;</P>
<P>Montoni, though not preci&s;ely what
Emily apprehended him to be&mdash;a captain
of banditti&mdash;had employed his troops in
enterpri&s;es not le&s;s daring, or le&s;s atrocious,
than &s;uch a character would have under|taken.
They had not only pillaged, when|ever
opportunity offered, the helple&s;s
<PB N="157" REF="159">
traveller, but had attacked, and plundered
the villas of &s;everal per&s;ons, which, being
&s;ituated among the &s;olitary rece&s;&s;es of the
mountains, were totally unprepared for re-&s;i&s;tance.
In the&s;e expeditions the com|manders
of the party did not appear, and
the men, partly di&s;gui&s;ed, had &s;ometimes
been mi&s;taken for common robbers, and,
at others, for bands of the foreign enemy,
who, at that period, invaded the country.
But, though they had already pillaged &s;eve|ral
man&s;ions, and brought home con&s;ider|able
trea&s;ures, they had ventured to ap|proach
only one ca&s;tle, in the attack of
