<BIBL>RlCHARD II.</BIBL></Q>
<P>We now return, for a moment, to
Venice, where Count Morano was &s;uffer|ing
under an accumulation of misfortunes.
Soon after his arrival in that city, he had
been arre&s;ted by order of the Senate, and,
without knowing of what he was &s;u&s;pected,
was conveyed to a place of confinement,
whither the mo&s;t &s;trenuous enquiries of his
