Who the enemy was, that had occa&s;ioned
him this calamity, he had not been able
to gue&s;s, unle&s;s, indeed, it was Montoni,
on whom his &s;u&s;picions re&s;ted, and not
only with much apparent probability, but
with ju&s;tice.</P>
<P><PB N="223" REF="225">
In the affair of the poi&s;oned cup, Mon|toni
had$ &s;u&s;pected Morano; but, being
unable to obtain the degree of proof,
which was nece&s;&s;ary to convict him of a
guilty intention he had recour&s;e to means
of other revenge, than he could hope to
