<P>&startq;How!&endq; exclaimed Emily.&startq; are any of the enemy here, then?&endq;
&startq;Nay, I don't know for that, now,&endq; he
<PB N="230" REF="232">
replied, &startq;but when I came away I &s;aw
one or two of them lying under the trees$&endq;</P>
<P>As they proceeded, the torch threw a
gloomy light upon the ground, and far
among the rece&s;&s;es of the woods, and
Emily feared to look forward, left &s;ome
object of horror &s;hould meet her eye.
The path was often &s;trewn with broken
heads of arrows, and with &s;hattered re|mains
of armour, &s;uch as at that period
was mingled with the lighter dre&s;s of the
$oldiers. &startq;Bring the light hither,&endq; &s;aid
Bertrand, &startq;I have &s;tumbled over &s;ome|thing,
that rattles loud enough.&endq; Ugo
holding up the torch, they perceived a
&s;teel brea&s;t- plate on the ground, which
