Pyren&eacute;es; a third fronted an avenue, be|yond
which the grey towers of Chateau|te-Blanc,
and a picture$que part of its ruin
were &s;een partially among the foliage;
while a fourth gave, between the trees, a
glimp&s;e of the green pa&s;tures and villages,
that diver&s;ify the banks of the Aude. The
Mediterranean, with the bold cliffs, that
<PB N="384" REF="386">
overlooked its &s;hores, were the grand ob|jects
